{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17479933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17479933"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:34:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:34:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20979"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20979"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.42,0.34,0.11,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13854"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100509"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13854","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13854"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20979"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82926"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1282"},{"type":"tags","id":"3798"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"13336"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33461"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34348"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44237"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100509","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100509"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent with a four-day history of cough, runny nose, and low-grade fever. The cough is worse at night and has been disrupting his sleep. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.3\u00b0C. Examination of his throat reveals mild erythema. His chest is clear on auscultation with no wheeze or crackles. There is no cervical lymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management for his nocturnal cough?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Amoxicillin 50 mg/kg oral suspension once daily","0.5 - 2 teaspoons of honey given at bedtime","Dextromethorphan syrup 10mL every 6-8 hours as needed","2-6 puffs of salbutamol MDI via spacer","Prednisolone 1mg/kg oral solution as a single dose"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with symptoms consistent with an uncomplicated upper respiratory tract infection (URTI). The clinical features include cough, runny nose, and low-grade fever without signs of lower respiratory tract involvement (clear chest on auscultation) or significant systemic illness. The main concern is the nocturnal cough disrupting sleep.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHoney\u003C/strong\u003E at bedtime is the most appropriate management for nocturnal cough in this three-year-old child. Evidence from systematic reviews supports honey as an effective symptomatic treatment for cough in children with URTIs. Honey has been shown to reduce cough frequency and severity and improve sleep quality for both the child and parents. The recommended dose is 0.5-2 teaspoons (2.5-10 mL) at bedtime. Honey is contraindicated in children under 12 months due to the risk of infant botulism, but is safe in this three-year-old.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDextromethorphan\u003C/strong\u003E syrup is an over-the-counter cough suppressant that is not recommended for children under six years of age in Australia. Evidence for its efficacy is limited, and it carries risks of adverse effects including paradoxical excitation, respiratory depression, and potential for accidental overdose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin\u003C/strong\u003E oral suspension would be inappropriate as this child has a viral URTI. There are no features suggesting bacterial infection such as high fever, purulent sputum, or focal chest signs. Unnecessary antibiotic use contributes to antimicrobial resistance and exposes the child to potential side effects without benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESalbutamol\u003C/strong\u003E inhaler via spacer would be indicated if there were signs of bronchospasm or wheeze, which are not present in this case. The child has a clear chest on auscultation with no history of asthma, making bronchodilator therapy unnecessary and potentially causing side effects such as tachycardia and tremor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E oral solution is a corticosteroid used for moderate to severe croup, acute asthma exacerbations, or other inflammatory respiratory conditions. It is not indicated for simple viral URTIs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Honey is effective for symptomatic relief of nocturnal cough in children over 12 months of age with upper respiratory tract infections.","Honey is contraindicated in children under 12 months of age due to the risk of infant botulism.","Over-the-counter cough medications are not recommended for children under 6 years of age in Australia due to risk of adverse effects."],"references":["RACGP Handbook of Non-Drug Interventions: Honey and cough in children with URTI. October 2014. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/handi/a-z/h/honey-and-cough-in-children-with-urti","Meeting requirements for over-the-counter (OTC) medicines containing dextromethorphan hydrobromide. Published Sept 2015, updated October 2024. Available at: https://www.tga.gov.au/resources/guidance/meeting-requirements-over-counter-otc-medicines-containing-dextromethorphan-hydrobromide"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82926"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20979"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82926"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-26T06:49:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-26T06:50:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13854"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100509"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms